body:
Rust rejects the following code ([playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=8213e0f5a7dfc0030d173f391bb38d24)):
```
use std::future::Future;
use std::pin::Pin;

async fn recurse(i: usize) {
    if i == 0 {
        println!("Zero!");
        return;
    }
    
    println!("entering {}", i);
    (Box::pin(recurse(i-1)) as Pin<Box<dyn Future<Output=()>>>).await;
    println!("exiting {}", i);
}

fn main() {
    futures::executor::block_on(recurse(10));
}
```
with the error message:
```
error[E0733]: recursion in an `async fn` requires boxing
 --> src/main.rs:4:28
  |
4 | async fn recurse(i: usize) {
  |                            ^ recursive `async fn`
  |
  = note: a recursive `async fn` must be rewritten to return a boxed `dyn Future`
```

But if the central part is changed to this ([playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=e3f96bb98df7c02cb4e0233f87184e22)):
```
    println!("entering {}", i);
    let recursed = Box::pin(recurse(i-1)) as Pin<Box<dyn Future<Output=()>>>;
    recursed.await;
    println!("exiting {}", i);
```
then Rust accepts the program.

[corrected] In neither program is the recursive future unboxed across an await, so there's no reason its size should contribute to the size of the future.

([internals forum thread](https://internals.rust-lang.org/t/recursive-async-function-permitted-but-why/12608))
